nd other analytic methods traditionally associated with literary criticism. Written especially for this collection, these essays argue for the importance of aesthetics, poetics, and aesthetic theory as they present new and stimulating perspectives on the directions which theory and criticism will take in the future. In addition to providing a selection of distinguished critics writing at their best, this collection is valuable because it represents a variety of fields and perspectives that are not usually found together in the same volume. Michael Clark's introduction provides a concise, cogent history of major developments and trends in literary theory from World War II to the present, making the entire volume essential reading for students and scholars of literature, literary theory, and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAesthetics, Modernx20th century. 0aAesthetics, Moderny20th century. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 4aaesthetics. 4alinguistics. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asemiotics. 4asocial philosophy. 4awar. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Hazard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehler, Ernst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Michael P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Michael P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDerrida, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonoghue, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFish, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIs